{{Infobox person
| name               = Alain Colas
| image              = Alain_Colas-Saint-Malo-1978-11.jpeg
| birth_place        = [[Clamecy, Nièvre]]
| death_place        = at sea
| caption            = Alain Colas in the cockpit of ''[[Pen Duick IV|Manureva]]'', a few days before the start of the first [[Route du Rhum]]
}}
'''Alain Colas''' (16 September 1943 – 16 November 1978)) was a French sailor, the first to complete a solitary round-the-world race in a multihull.<ref name="CapHornHommeSeul">{{cite book|last=Colas|first=Alain|title=Cap Horn pour un homme seul|year=1977|publisher=Flammarion|location=[Paris]|isbn=978-2080650092}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Colas|first=Alain|title=Cap Horn pour un homme seul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTgNAQAAIAAJ&q=alain+colas&dq=alain+colas&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=usSMUfX3FtOUhQem04HACw&redir_esc=y|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref> He met [[Éric Tabarly]] in [[Sydney]] in 1967, and bought [[Manureva|Pen Duick IV]] from him in 1970, and won the [[Single-Handed Trans-Atlantic Race|"Transat"]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite book|last=Colas|first=Alain|title=Un tour du monde pour une victoire|year=2003|publisher=Arthaud|location=Paris|isbn=978-2700395969|edition=Nouv. éd.}}</ref> In 1972, he started the construction of a 72m (236 feet) 4 masted monohull for the 1976 [[Single-Handed Trans-Atlantic Race|"Transat"]].<ref name="CapHornHommeSeul" /> He broke his right ankle, underwent 22 surgeries, and got back on his feet for the solitary transatlantic race. [[Éric Tabarly]] won, and Alain Colas arrived 2nd but was classed 5th. On 5 November 1978, he took part in his last race, the first [[Route du Rhum]]. On 16 November 1978, as he passed the Azores, he sent his last radio message saying that everything was alright and sailing well. Neither his boat ''[[Manureva]]'' nor his body were ever found.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alain Colas, Rêves d'Océan|url=http://bourgogne.france3.fr/2013/01/22/un-documentaire-exceptionnel-sur-alain-colas-le-navigateur-de-manureva-185723.html|publisher=France 3 Bourgogne|accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=William Oscar|title=A Legend Lost At Sea|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1094498/index.htm|accessdate=10 May 2013|date=8 January 1979|work=CNN}}</ref>

