{{for|the minor planet|10199 Chariklo}}
'''Chariclo''' ({{IPAc-en|k|ə|ˈ|r|ɪ|k|l|oʊ}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|ær|ᵻ|k|l|oʊ}}; {{lang-grc|Χαρικλώ|Khariklṓ|graceful spinner}};<ref>[http://perseus.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.21:1:41.Slater William J. Slater, ''Lexicon to Pindar'', Trustees of Tufts University, Berlin, [1969<nowiki>]</nowiki>].</ref><ref>"[http://www.20knames.com/female_k_names_3.htm {{Formatnum:20000}} Names from Around the World]".</ref> ) is either of two [[nymph]]s in [[Greek mythology]]:
* Chariclo, daughter of [[Cychreus]] and [[Stilbe]] married the [[centaur]] [[Chiron]] and became the mother of [[Hippe]], [[Endeïs]], [[Ocyrhoe]], and [[Carystus (mythology)|Carystus]].
* Chariclo, a [[nymph]] devotee of [[Athena]], who became pregnant by a shepherd, Everes, giving birth to the prophet [[Tiresias]]. Tiresias was struck blind by Athena after seeing her naked. Chariclo begged Athena to give him sight back, but the goddess could not undo her curse.  She gave him the gift of prophecy instead. His husband Everes was a descendant of Udaeus, the [[Spartoi|Spartan]].<ref>[[Pseudo-|Pseudo]]-[[Apollodorus of Athens|Apollodorus]]. ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.6.7&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0022 3.6.7]''</ref>

