{{short description|A sea state with two wave systems traveling at oblique angles}}
[[File:Ile de ré.JPG|thumb|300px|Cross swell at [[Île de Ré]] ]]
In surface [[navigation]], a '''cross sea''' is a [[sea state]] with two [[wind wave|wave system]]s traveling at [[oblique angle]]s.<ref name=AMS>{{cite web | url=http://amsglossary.allenpress.com/glossary/search?id=cross-sea1 |work=Glossary of Meteorology | publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]]| title=Cross Sea |accessdate=2007-11-28 }}</ref> This may occur when [[water waves]] from one [[weather system]] continue despite a shift in [[wind]]. Waves generated by the new wind run at an angle to the old, creating a shifting, dangerous pattern. Two weather systems that are far from each other may create a cross sea when the waves from the systems meet, usually at a place far from either weather system. Until the older waves have dissipated, they create a sea hazard among the most perilous. This sea state is fairly common and a larger percentage of ship accidents were found to have occurred in this state.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Is the Cross Sea Dangerous?|publisher=[[European Space Agency]]|date=2010|accessdate=5 June 2016|url=http://earth.eo.esa.int/cgi-bin/confsea10.pl?abstract=349|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503193016/http://earth.eo.esa.int/cgi-bin/confsea10.pl?abstract=349|archivedate=3 May 2014|df=}}</ref> Vessels fare better against large waves when perpendicular to the wave. In a cross sea, vessels are much more likely to be struck in a dangerous way.

A '''cross swell''' is generated when the wave systems are longer period [[Swell (ocean)|swell]], rather than short period wind generated waves.<ref>{{cite book | first=Nathaniel | last=Bowditch | authorlink = Nathaniel Bowditch | title=[[The American Practical Navigator]] | publisher=[[National Imagery and Mapping Agency]]|chapter=Glossary C| chapterurl=http://www.irbs.com/bowditch/pdf/glossary/gloss-c.pdf| location= Bethesda, MD | year=1995 | isbn=0-403-09895-5 | page=758 }}
</ref>

