{{energy-stub}}

[[File:World energy consumption.svg|thumb|300px|The world's increasing demand for energy<ref name="BP-Review-2013">BP: [http://www.bp.com/statisticalreview Statistical Review of World Energy], Workbook </ref>]]
[[File:Total World Energy Consumption by Source 2010.png|thumb|right|350px|World energy mix in 2010]]
[[File:Total World Energy Consumption by Source 2013.png|thumb|right|350px|World energy mix in 2013]]
[[File:World total primary energy production.png|thumb|left|World total primary energy production by country]]
[[File:Electricity percentage worldwide by source-semilog.png|thumb|left|Electricity percentage worldwide by source with forecast]]

The '''energy mix''' is a group of different [[primary energy|primary]] [[Source of energy|energy sources]] from which [[secondary energy]] for direct use - usually [[electricity]] - is [[energy production|produced]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planete-energies.com/en/medias/explanations/about-energy-mix|title=About the Energy Mix}}</ref> Primary energy in the form of fossil fuels is nowadays still mostly used directly for [[motor]]-driven [[vehicle]]s, i.e. [[transport]]. Further [[energy conversion]] of the co-produced [[waste heat]] after burning is not possible.

In 2007, the [[World energy consumption|global primary energy use]] corresponded to {{convert|12.5|e6t}} [[oil equivalent]] corresponding to {{convert|145,375|GWh}}). According to the [[International Energy Agency]] (IEA) 13,6% of that was used by the [[EU]]. Within the EU, 75.9% came from [[fossil fuel]]s, 14.1% from [[nuclear power|nuclear energy]], 7% from [[biofuel]]s, 2.9 from [[renewable energy]] resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpb.de/nachschlagen/zahlen-und-fakten/europa/75140/themengrafik-energiemix-nach-staaten|title=Energiemix nach Staaten (Energy mix by country)|language=German|publisher=Bundeszentrale für politische Bildung}}</ref>

Overall primary energy consumption in the U.S. in 2015 relied most on [[petroleum]] ([[orders of magnitude (energy)|{{convert|35|e15BTU}}]]), natural gas ({{convert|29|e15BTU|abbr=on}}) and coal ({{convert|16|e15BTU|abbr=on}}). Renewables contributed {{convert|9|e15BTU|abbr=on}} and nuclear power {{convert|8|e15BTU|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 21, 2016|title=Changing U.S. energy mix reflects growing use of natural gas, petroleum, and renewables|url=https://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.cfm?id=27172|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>
In the same year, about 4 million GWh of [[electricity generation|electricity were generated]] in the U.S., 67% of which was generated from fossil fuels (coal, natural gas, and < 1% petroleum), 20% from nuclear power, 6% [[hydropower]] and 7% other renewables.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eia.gov/tools/faqs/faq.cfm?id=427&t=3|title=FAQ: What is U.S. electricity generation by energy source?|accessdate=2016-08-15|publisher=[[U.S. Energy Information Administration|EIA]]}}</ref>

While the rise of global [[energy consumption]] with the global [[population growth]] cannot immediately be counteracted, the [[sustainable growth|sustainability of growth]] can partially be improved by changing the energy mix towards renewables. The main forces in this process are national and transnational [[energy policy]] and the [[energy industry]] together with their [[energy lobby|lobbyists]].

