.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500774</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''F1'''</big> |'''N of [[Lawton, Kansas|Lawton]] to E of [[Asbury, Missouri|Asbury, MO]]''' |[[Cherokee County, Kansas|Cherokee]], [[Jasper County, Missouri|Jasper (MO)]] | |0046 |{{convert|5|mi|km|}} |Tornado touched down near the Kansas state line and crossed into Missouri, where a few outbuildings were destroyed.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5504547</ref> |- |colspan="7" align=center|'''[[Nebraska]]''' |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''S of [[Adams, Nebraska|Adams]]''' |[[Gage County, Nebraska|Gage]] | |2300 |{{convert|6|mi|km|}} |Tornado tore the roofs off of three hog barns and a chicken shed, and blew out windows at several houses. Trees were damaged as well.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500781</ref> |- |colspan="7" align=center|'''[[Arkansas]]''' |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''SW of [[Marble Falls, Arkansas|Marble Falls]]''' |[[Newton County, Arkansas|Newton]] | |0255 |{{convert|1.7|mi|km|}} |A few trees were snapped off or uprooted.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5502394</ref> |- |colspan="7" | <small>Sources: [http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/060406_rpts.html SPC Storm Reports for 04/06], [http://www.crh.noaa.gov/crnews/display_story.php?wfo=oax&storyid=2149&source=0 Omaha NWS office] [http://www.srh.noaa.gov/tsa/ Tulsa office] [http://www.crh.noaa.gov/ict/scripts/viewstory.php?STORY_NUMBER=2006040718 Wichita office] [http://www.crh.noaa.gov/top/?n=storms040606 Topeka office], [http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/html/svr0406b.htm Little Rock office], [http://www.crh.noaa.gov/product.php?site=SGF&product=LSR&issuedby=SGF Springfield office], [http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~storms National Climatic Data Center]</small> |}
===April 7 event=== {| class="wikitable collapsible" style="width:100%;" !colspan="7"|List of reported tornadoes - Friday, April 7, 2006 |- |<center>'''[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]'''</center> || <center>'''Location'''</center> || <center>'''County / Parish'''</center> || <center>'''Coord.'''</center> || <center>'''Time (UTC)'''</center> || <center>'''Path length'''</center> || <center>'''Comments/Damage'''</center> |- |colspan="7" align=center|'''[[Tennessee]]''' |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''SW of [[Big Sandy, Tennessee|Big Sandy]]''' |[[Benton County, Tennessee|Benton]] | |1740 |{{convert|1.1|mi|km|}} |Homes sustained shingle damage in the Cedar Lake Estates subdivision, and several trees were downed.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500665</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''NW of [[Waverly, Tennessee|Waverly]]''' |[[Humphreys County, Tennessee|Humphreys]] | |1805 |{{convert|0.2|mi|m|}} |Two houses suffered roof damage and several trees were downed.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500667</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''NE of [[Waverly, Tennessee|Waverly]]''' |[[Humphreys County, Tennessee|Humphreys]] | |1810 |{{convert|0.2|mi|m|}} |Several outbuildings were damaged and a barn was destroyed.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500668</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat3}} | <big>'''F3'''</big> |'''NE of [[Charlotte, Tennessee|Charlotte]] to [[Ashland City, Tennessee|Ashland City]]''' |[[Dickson County, Tennessee|Dickson]], [[Cheatham County, Tennessee|Cheatham]] | |1830 |{{convert|19|mi|km|}} |Near Charlotte, the tornado destroyed three mobile homes, flipped vehicles, and downed many trees. As the tornado passed near [[Bellsburg, Tennessee|Bellsburg]], a poorly constructed house was swept away and scattered into a wooded area, with only the basement and garage remaining. A truck was blown into the basement of the home. A small grocery store was also destroyed in the area. In Dickson County, a total of 25 homes were destroyed, 8 homes had major damage, and 24 homes and businesses had moderate damage. In Cheatham County, one home was destroyed, 13 homes had major damage, and 9 homes, along with farms and businesses had moderate damage. In the town of [[Greenbrier, Tennessee|Greenbrier]], homes had shingles torn off and large trees were downed. Tornado struck Ashland City before dissipating, where many trees and a large communications tower were downed, and homes sustained roof damage.<ref>http://www.srh.noaa.gov/ohx/?n=stormsurvey04072006</ref><ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500705</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''F2'''</big> |'''[[Parker Crossroads, Tennessee|Parker Crossroads]] to E of [[Yuma, Tennessee|Yuma]]''' |[[Henderson County, Tennessee|Henderson]], [[Carroll County, Tennessee|Carroll]] | |1834 |{{convert|9|mi|km|}} |Damage in Henderson County was limited to trees. In Carroll County, the tornado struck the town of Yuma, where 15 homes were destroyed and 29 homes were damaged. The Yuma Church of Christ sustained significant roof damage, and numerous trees and power lines were downed. 5 people were injured.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5506839</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''F1'''</big> |'''[[Sardis, Tennessee|Sardis]]''' |[[Henderson County, Tennessee|Henderson]] | |1840 |{{convert|4|mi|km|}} |Many trees and power lines were downed, and headstones were knocked over at the Sardis Cemetery.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5506840</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''F2'''</big> |'''S of [[Camden, Tennessee|Camden]]''' |[[Benton County, Tennessee|Benton]] | |1853 |{{convert|6|mi|km|}} |One home was destroyed, and 15 other homes and businesses had major damage. One home lost its entire roof, and other homes had roof damage. Numerous large trees were snapped, uprooted or blown down.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500664</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''F1'''</big> |'''W of [[Hurricane Mills, Tennessee|Hurricane Mills]]''' |[[Humphreys County, Tennessee|Humphreys]] | |1905 |{{convert|4.5|mi|km|}} |Many large trees were downed, a brick home was heavily damaged, and a mobile home was completely destroyed with only the frame left. Another mobile home was shifted off of its foundation.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500666</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat3}} | <big>'''F3'''</big> |'''[[Goodlettsville, Tennessee|Goodlettsville]] to [[Gallatin, Tennessee|Gallatin]]''' |[[Davidson County, Tennessee|Davidson]], [[Sumner County, Tennessee|Sumner]] | |1908 |{{convert|23|mi|km|}} |'''7 deaths''' - Tornado first struck Goodlettsville, where major damage occurred and some small homes were leveled. Some businesses in town were also destroyed, including the Metro Baptist Church. 21 homes were destroyed, 13 homes or businesses were heavily damaged, and 31 others sustained moderate damage in that area. The tornado then struck [[Hendersonville, Tennessee|Hendersonville]], where 80 homes were destroyed. The tornado then tore through Gallatin, where 700 homes were destroyed, along with several car dealerships and other businesses. Many vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the Volunteer State Community College was heavily damaged. All seven fatalities occurred in Gallatin, and some homes were swept away at that location (though damage surveyors determined that they were poorly built). 128 people were injured.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500766</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''NE of [[Hohenwald, Tennessee|Hohenwald]]''' |[[Lewis County, Tennessee|Lewis]] | |1943 |{{convert|0.3|mi|m|}} |A few trees were snapped.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500669</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''F1'''</big> |'''[[McMinnville, Tennessee|McMinnville]] area''' |[[Warren County, Tennessee|Warren]] | |2145 |{{convert|11|mi|km|}} |'''2 deaths''' - Shingles were torn off of roofs and large trees were downed. A barn was heavily damaged as well. The two fatalities occurred when a mobile home was destroyed.<ref>http://www.srh.noaa.gov/ohx/?n=stormsurvey04072006#summary</ref><ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500706</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''F1'''</big> |'''S of [[Crossville, Tennessee|Crossville]]''' |[[Cumberland County, Tennessee|Cumberland]] | |2246 |{{convert|6.2|mi|km|}} |Four homes and two mobile homes were destroyed out of 181 homes that were damaged. Outbuildings and vehicles were damaged as well.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500730</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''[[Chestnut Ridge, Tennessee|Chestnut Ridge]]''' |[[Lincoln County, Tennessee|Lincoln]], [[Moore County, Tennessee|Moore]] | |2317 |{{convert|30|yd|m|}} |Damage was limited to trees.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5499692</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''F1'''</big> |'''SW of [[McMinnville, Tennessee|McMinnville]]''' |[[Warren County, Tennessee|Warren]] | |2328 |{{convert|4|mi|km|}} |'''1 death''' - There was extensive damage to a barn, a cinder block building, and numerous trees. Several outbuildings were destroyed and a shed was turned onto its side. Homes in the Country Club subdivision sustained roof damage, and a fatality occurred in a mobile home.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=5500707</ref> |- |bgcolor=#{{Storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''F0'''</big> |'''E of [[Mulberry, Tennessee|Mulberry]]''' |[[Lincoln County, Tennessee|Lincoln]] | |2330 |{{convert|200|yd|m|}} |Homes sustained minor 