[[Category:Metaphors referring to animals]]
[[Category:Legendary turtles]]

'''Zanahary''' is the [[sky deity|personified sky]] of [[Malagasy mythology|Malagasy mythologies and folklores]]. He (usually male, but sometimes considered genderless<ref>Arthur Cotterell, A Dictionary of World Mythology, Oxford University Press, 17/04/1986</ref>) is considered a creator god, having collaborated with the earth god [[Ratovantany]] to create humanity; upon death, the soul migrates to the firmament, while the body returns to the earth.<ref>[https://www.scilt.org.uk/portals/24/passeport2/educationscotland/Images/MadagascarCreationMyth_tcm4-730169.pdf]</ref><ref>Arthur Cotterell, A Dictionary of World Mythology, Oxford University Press, 17/04/1986</ref> For this reason, Zanahary is closely associated with the soul in the indigenous theology as well as ancestor worship.<ref>Littleton, C. Scott (2005). Gods, goddesses, and mythology. Marshall Cavendish. p. 74. {{ISBN|9780761475590}}.</ref> He is a national god of the [[Merina]] people, and frequently henceforth appealed to by Malagasy nationalist groups; most notably [[Ranavalona I]] promoted the worship of this god over [[Christianity]].
The [[Bara people]] and [[Betsimisaraka people]] possess a myth in which the role of Zanahary is taken by the [[solar deity|personified sun]], which accepts souls after death;<ref>"ASK BALLADEER: IS THERE A MALAGASY SOLAR DEITY?". Balladeer's Blog. 2018-06-03. Retrieved 2018-06-14.</ref> however Zanahary is typically assumed to be devoid of solar characteristics. Similarly there is an "earth Zanahary" in contrast to the sky.<ref>Arthur Cotterell, A Dictionary of World Mythology, Oxford University Press, 17/04/1986</ref>
